</table>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-ratio-airspeed1">
	<webwork>
		<statement>
			<p>The calculation for distance over a half hour suggests a general method for using a rate. Use this method to calculate how far the plane would travel in 3.1 hours <var name="'341'" width="4" /></p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p><md>
				<mrow>\frac{110 \text{ nautical miles}}{1 \text{ hour}} \amp = \frac{110 \text{ nautical miles}}{1 \text{ hour}} \cdot \frac{3.1}{3.1}</mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \frac{341 \text{ nautical miles}}{3.1 \text{ hours}}.</mrow>
			</md></p>
		</solution>
    </webwork>
</exercise>

<example xml:id="example-ratio-airspeed-solve">
	<title>Proportion: Solving</title>
	<p>The Diamond DA-20 cruises at the rate of <me>\frac{110 \text{ nautical miles}}{1 \text{ hour}}</me>.</p>
	<p>How long will it take to travel 236 nm?</p>
	<p>Because this is a fixed ratio we can write
		<md>
			<mrow>\frac{110 \text{ nm}}{1 \text{ hour}} \amp = \frac{236 \text{ nm}}{t \text{ hours}}.</mrow>
			<mrow>t \text{ hours} \cdot \frac{110 \text{ nm}}{1 \text{ hour}} \amp = t \text{ hours} \cdot \frac{236 \text{ nm}}{t \text{ hours}}.</mrow>
			<mrow>t \cdot 110 \text{ nm} \amp = 236 \text{ nm}.</mrow>
			<mrow>t \cdot 110 \text{ nm} / 110 \text{ nm}  \amp = 236 \text{ nm}/ 110 \text{ nm}.</mrow>
			<mrow>t \amp = \frac{236}{110}.</mrow>
			<mrow>t \amp \approx 2.1.</mrow>
		</md>
	</p>
</example>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-ratio-climb">
	<webwork>
		<statement>
			<p>If the Diamond DA-20 climbs at the rate of <me>\frac{450 \text{ feet}}{1.0 \text{ minute}}</me> how long will it take it to climb 2500 ft? <var name="'5.5'" width="4" /></p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>	<md>
				<mrow>\frac{450 \text{ ft}}{1.0 \text{ minute}} \amp = \frac{2500 \text{ ft}}{t \text{ minutes}}.</mrow>
				<mrow>t \text{ minutes} \cdot \frac{450 \text{ ft}}{1.0 \text{ minutes}} \amp = t \text{ minutes} \cdot \frac{2500 \text{ ft}}{t \text{ minutes}}.</mrow>
				<mrow>t \cdot 450 \text{ ft} \amp = 2500 \text{ ft}.</mrow>
				<mrow>t \cdot 450 \text{ ft} / 450 \text{ ft}  \amp = 2500 \text{ ft}/ 450 \text{ ft}.</mrow>
				<mrow>t \amp = \frac{2500}{450}</mrow>
				<mrow>t \amp \approx 5.5.</mrow>
			</md></p>
		</solution>
    </webwork>
</exercise>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-ratio-conversion">
	<title>Conversion of Units</title>

	<p>Rates include units like feet per minute or gallons per hour. Sometimes we convert one unit to another.</p>

	<example xml:id="example-unit-conversion1">
		<statement><p>We will convert 2.1 hours to a number of minutes. Note we know there are 60 minutes per hour. Notice that the conversion is like a rate. Specifically it is a fraction. If we multiply minutes/hour by hours we will end up with just minutes.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			<md>
				<mrow>2.1 \text{ hours} \cdot \frac{60 \text{ minutes}}{\text{hour}} &amp; =</mrow>
				<mrow>2.1 \cdot 60 \cdot \frac{\cancelhighlight{\text{hours}}}{\cancelhighlight{\text{hour}}} \text{ minutes} &amp; =</mrow>
				<mrow>126 \text{ minutes}. &amp;</mrow>
			</md>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<example xml:id="example-unit-conversion2">
		<statement><p>We will convert 450 feet per minute to units of inches per second. Note we know there are 12 inches per foot and 60 seconds per minute. We need to divide by feet, multiply by inches, divide by minutes, and multiply by seconds to have the units divide out as desired. That is we multiply by the ratios 12 inches/foot and 60 seconds/minute.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{450 \text{ feet}}{1 \text{ minute}} \cdot \frac{12 \text{ inches}}{1 \text{ foot}} \cdot \frac{1 \text{ minute}}{60 \text{ seconds}} &amp; = </mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{450 \cdot 12}{60} \frac{\cancelhighlight{\text{ feet}}}{\cancelhighlight{\text{ foot}}} \cdot \frac{\secondcancelhighlight{\text{ minute}}}{\secondcancelhighlight{\text{ minute}}} \cdot \frac{\text{ inches}}{\text{ second}} &amp; = </mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{90 \text{ inches}}{1 \text{ second}}.</mrow>
			</md>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<example xml:id="example-unit-conversion-metric">
		<statement><p>We will convert 450 feet per minute to units of meters per minute. Note when converting between dissimilar units the conversions are approximations: select a sufficiently precise approximation for your application. For this problem we will use the ratio of one foot per 0.3048 meters. We will need to divide by feet and multiply by meters so we need to reciprocate this ratio.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{450 \text{ feet}}{\text{ minute}} \cdot \frac{0.3048 \text{ meters}}{\text{ foot}} &amp; = </mrow>
				<mrow>450 \cdot 0.3048 \frac{\cancelhighlight{\text{ feet}}}{\cancelhighlight{\text{ foot}}} \cdot \frac{\text{ meters}}{\text{ minute}} &amp; \approx </mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{140 \text{ meters}}{\text{ minute}}.</mrow>
			</md>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<exercise xml:id="exercise-convert-units">
		<webwork>
			<statement>
				<p>Look up the conversion from kilometers to miles. How many miles per hour is 12 kilometers per hour? <var name="'7.5'" width="4" /></p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>	<md>
					<mrow>\frac{12 \text{ km}}{\text{ hour}} \amp \approx </mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{12 \text{ km}}{\text{ hour}} \cdot \frac{0.621371 \text{ miles}}{\text{km}} \amp \approx </mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{7.5 \text{ miles}}{\text{hour}} \cdot \frac{\cancelhighlight{\text{km}}}{\cancelhighlight{\text{km}}} \amp \approx </mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{7.5 \text{ miles}}{\text{hour}}.</mrow>
				</md></p>
			</solution>
	    </webwork>
	</exercise>

	<example xml:id="example-unit-conversion-square">
		<statement><p>We will convert 153 square inches to square centimeters. Note that 1 inch is approximately 2.54 centimeters. Note first that <term>square</term> here refers to the inches not to the 153. Notice also how we adjust the conversion process for this exponent.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			<md>
				<mrow>153 \text{ inches}^2 &amp; = </mrow>
				<mrow>153 \text{ inches}^2 \cdot \left(\frac{2.54 \text{ cm}}{\text{ inch}}\right)^2 &amp; \approx </mrow>
				<mrow>153 \text{ inches}^2 \cdot \frac{6.45 \text{ cm}^2}{\text{ inch}^2} &amp; \approx </mrow>
				<mrow>987 \text{ cm}^2 \cdot \frac{ \cancelhighlight{\text{ inches}^2}}{ \cancelhighlight{\text{ inch}^2}}. &amp; \approx</mrow>
				<mrow>987 \text{ cm}^2.</mrow>
			</md>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<exercise xml:id="exercise-convert-units-squared">
		<webwork>
			<statement>
				<p>Note that a pound (lb) is a unit of <term>force</term>. It is approximately equal to 4.45 Newtons which is another unit of force. How many Newtons per square meter is 51.2 lbs per square inch? Look up other conversions as needed. <var name="'228'" width="5" /></p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p><md>
					<mrow>\frac{51.2 \text{ lbs}}{\text{ inch}^2} \amp \approx </mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{51.2 \text{ lbs}}{\text{ inch}^2} \cdot  \frac{1.00 \text{ N}}{4.45 \text{ lbs}} \cdot \left(\frac{1.00 \text{ inch}}{0.254 \text{ m}}\right)^2 \amp \approx </mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{51.2}{4.45 \cdot 0.0254^2} \frac{\text{lbs}}{\text{inch}^2} \cdot  \frac{\text{N}}{\text{lbs}} \cdot \frac{\text{inch}^2}{\text{m}^2} \amp \approx </mrow>
					<mrow>17833 \frac{ \cancelhighlight{\text{lbs}}}{\secondcancelhighlight{\text{ inch}^2}} \cdot \frac{\text{N}}{\cancelhighlight{\text{lbs}}} \cdot \frac{\secondcancelhighlight{\text{ inch}^2}}{\text{m}^2} \amp \approx </mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{17800 \text{ N}}{\text{m}^2}.</mrow>
				</md></p>
			</solution>
	    </webwork>
	</exercise>

</subsection>

</section>
